said the U.S. needed a more
muscular deportation

19:00.106 --> 19:01.907 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
force:

19:01.941 --> 19:03.609 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP, President of the
United States:
We're getting really bad dudes
out of this

19:03.642 --> 19:07.680 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
country, and at a rate that
nobody's seen
before.

19:07.713 --> 19:10.549 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And they're the bad ones.

19:10.583 --> 19:12.151 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And it's a military operation.

19:12.184 --> 19:16.022 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: In Mexico
City, Kelly seemed
to walk back his boss' words.

19:16.055 --> 19:22.161 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN KELLY: No, repeat, no use
of military
force in immigration operations,
none.

19:22.194 --> 19:26.665 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: The White
House press secretary
later sought to clarify the
president's comments.

19:26.699 --> 19:29.001 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SEAN SPICER, White House Press
Secretary:
The president was using that as
an adjective.

19:29.035 --> 19:30.936 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's happening with precision.

19:30.970 --> 19:35.307 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: The visit,
billed as reassurance
to concerned Mexican
counterparts, comes amid

19:35.341 --> 19:37.610 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
heightened tensions between the
neighbors.

19:37.643 --> 19:42.681 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Earlier this week, a memo from
the Department
of Homeland Security vastly
expanded the government's

19:42.715 --> 19:47.720 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
mandate to quickly deport
immigrants not convicted
of serious crimes.

19:47.753 --> 19:52.324 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The memo also said anyone caught
illegally
crossing the southern border
would be sent

19:52.358 --> 19:56.395 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
back to Mexico, regardless of
their home country.

19:56.429 --> 20:00.766 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
President Trump has ordered a
review of all
aid to Mexico, raising
speculation that the

20:00.800 --> 20:06.772 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
administration may cut those
funds to pay
for Mr. Trump's long-promised
border wall.

20:06.806 --> 20:11.143 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Concerned Mexicans have urged
President Enrique
Pena Nieto's government to stand
up to the

20:11.177 --> 20:12.945 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Trump administration.

20:12.978 --> 20:17.283 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
With Tillerson at his side,
Mexico's foreign
minister called for dialogue,
but said his

20:17.316 --> 20:21.253 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
country was -- quote -- "worried
and irritated"
by the policy shifts.

20:21.287 --> 20:24.957 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LUIS VIDEGARAY, Mexican Foreign
Minister (through
translator): In order to
overcome the insults,

20:24.990 --> 20:29.728 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
to overcome the negative
feelings that, without
a doubt today prevail, what will
matter are

20:29.762 --> 20:31.564 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the actions, more than the
words.

20:31.597 --> 20:36.235 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Tillerson said
it was natural
for two strong countries to
disagree, but

20:36.268 --> 20:38.070 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that progress had been made.

20:38.104 --> 20:41.107 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
REX TILLERSON, U.S. Secretary of
State: There's
no mistaking that the rule of
law matters

20:41.140 --> 20:43.109 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
along both sides of our border.

20:43.142 --> 20:47.746 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We discussed the importance of
fair treatment
of all those in this transit.

20:47.780 --> 20:51.684 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Later,
Tillerson and Kelly
met the Mexican president, who
has sparred

20:51.717 --> 20:57.289 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with Mr. Trump both during
campaign and since
the inauguration, over the wall,
immigration

20:57.323 --> 20:59.158 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and trade.

20:59.191 --> 21:02.962 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Joining me now to discuss the
trip to Mexico
and how Secretary Tillerson's
State Department

21:02.995 --> 21:05.998 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is taking shape are Gardiner
Harris of The
New York Times.

21:06.031 --> 21:07.500 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He's in Mexico City right now.

21:07.533 --> 21:10.636 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And Yeganeh Torbati, she covers
the State
Department for Reuters.

21:10.669 --> 21:12.471 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Gardiner, let me start with you.

21:12.505 --> 21:16.842 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The word choice by the president
to say military
operation today, and Secretary
Kelly going

21:16.876 --> 21:20.312 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
out of his way to make sure that
everyone
knew that it wasn't the
military, it almost

21:20.346 --> 21:23.582 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
made it seem like there were two
messengers,
two messages, two teams.

21:23.616 --> 21:26.085 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GARDINER HARRIS, The New York
Times: Right.

21:26.118 --> 21:30.623 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, that's been the problem
all along during
the Trump administration,
particularly for

21:30.656 --> 21:32.391 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the State Department.

21:32.424 --> 21:37.530 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And leaders around the world are
having trouble
figuring out who they should
listen to.

21:37.563 --> 21:42.535 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Should they listen to the State
Department
and Rex Tillerson, who is very
straight?

21:42.568 --> 21:45.404 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He's sort of a traditional
Republican.

21:45.437 --> 21:53.579 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's trying to keep alliances
and ties across
the world to our various allies,
particularly

21:53.612 --> 21:54.980 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
with Mexico.

21:55.014 --> 22:00.352 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Or should they listen to the
more bombastic
statements from Trump?

22:00.386 --> 22:04.190 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Tillerson was in Europe last
week trying to
calm everything down.

22:04.223 --> 22:09.395 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So was Mike Pence, saying that
we value NATO,
we value E.U.

22:09.428 --> 22:13.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But those are not messages that
President
Trump has said.

22:13.599 --> 22:15.768 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
He's insulted the E.U.

22:15.801 --> 22:16.902 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
He's insulted NATO.

22:16.936 --> 22:19.338 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the same thing is going on
in Mexico right
now.

22:19.371 --> 22:27.479 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In fact, just today, as you
played, the president
had talked to a bunch of CEOs in
a roundtable,

22:27.513 --> 22:32.751 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and he mentioned Mexico five or
six different
times, suggesting that Mexico
has really been

22:32.785 --> 22:38.390 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
stealing jobs from the United
States, has
this $70 billion trade surplus,
and that that

22:38.424 --> 22:40.159 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
has to stop.

22:40.192 --> 22:44.496 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And he sort of said, look, I
want to have
good relations with Mexico, but,
if we don't,

22:44.530 --> 22:46.465 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
we don't.

22:46.498 --> 22:53.472 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so that gives, obviously,
some very difficult
times for the diplomats here,
who are trying

22:53.505 --> 23:00.145 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to certainly change some things
about immigration
and enforcement with the
Mexicans, but keeping

23:00.179 --> 23:05.951 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
what has been a vital alliance
with the Mexicans,
because the Mexicans, of course,
there is

23:05.985 --> 23:10.456 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
not now any immigration of
Mexicans in the
United States.

23:10.489 --> 23:13.626 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Most of the immigration is from
Central America.

23:13.659 --> 23:18.264 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the Mexicans are crucial
allies in slowing
that immigration.

23:18.297 --> 23:21.166 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Yeganeh
Torbati, we were
just saying you have been
covering the State

23:21.200 --> 23:22.735 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Department.

23:22.768 --> 23:25.838 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But there haven't been any daily
press briefings
since Mr. Tillerson took office.

23:25.871 --> 23:31.076 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is also, in some ways, the
opposite of
the personality of John Kerry,
who put himself

23:31.110 --> 23:33.912 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the middle of everything, was
taking questions
all the time.

23:33.946 --> 23:35.381 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
YEGANEH TORBATI, Reuters: Right.

23:35.414 --> 23:38.117 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I mean, Secretary Tillerson
comes from a very
different background.

23:38.150 --> 23:42.955 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He comes from a private sector
background
and then, in particular, from
ExxonMobil,

23:42.988 --> 23:46.859 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
where they really weren't
well-known for their
public engagement or their
engagement with

23:46.892 --> 23:48.694 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the press.

23:48.727 --> 23:51.563 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, just as you said, there
hasn't been a
State Department press briefing
since January

23:51.597 --> 23:55.668 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
19, the last full day of
President Obama's
presidency.

23:55.701 --> 24:01.273 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that has taken away a
megaphone that the
State Department traditionally
has to speak

24:01.307 --> 24:05.811 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
on issues of international
importance, not
only to put their own views out
there, but

24:05.844 --> 24:08.180 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
also to respond to other
countries.

24:08.213 --> 24:11.817 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that briefing is not just
useful for reporters
like myself.

24:11.850 --> 24:17.656 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's also looked to very closely
by countries
around the world, both allies
and adversaries,

24:17.690 --> 24:23.862 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for clues on, what is the U.S.
policy towards
Israeli settlements, towards the
arrests of

24:23.896 --> 24:28.967 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
journalists by Turkey, for
example, and other
things that may happen around
the world?

24:29.001 --> 24:32.338 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And it's also looked to within
the State Department.

24:32.371 --> 24:37.176 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Preparing the different bureaus
for that press
briefing, sending up talking
points, is part

24:37.209 --> 24:40.012 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of sometimes the policy process
itself.

24:40.045 --> 24:44.283 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And without that daily kind of
organizing
structure, there is a little bit
of a sense

24:44.316 --> 24:48.020 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of loss right now at the State
Department
within those kind of lower ranks
and within

24:48.053 --> 24:49.855 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the bureaus.

24:49.888 --> 24:52.257 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Gardiner
Harris, today,
we heard the Mexican leaders
say, we're willing

24:52.291 --> 24:56.128 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to talk about immigration, but
we also want
to talk about trade and
security.

24:56.161 --> 24:57.963 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Why did they want to lump those
in?

24:57.996 --> 25:00.232 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
GARDINER HARRIS: Well, exactly.

25:00.265 --> 25:04.436 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, for the Mexicans, of
course, there's
a lot of issues that happen at
the border,

25:04.470 --> 25:08.307 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
not just issues that are of
concern to the
United States, but are issues
that are of

25:08.340 --> 25:10.142 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
concern to Mexico.

25:10.175 --> 25:13.312 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For instance, there is a huge
amount of guns
that come from the United States
into Mexico.

25:13.345 --> 25:18.684 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is a lot of bulk cash that
comes from
the United States into Mexico
that feeds the

25:18.717 --> 25:21.653 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
narco-trafficking gangs in
Mexico.

25:21.687 --> 25:28.394 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, Mexico, of course, wants to
expand the
list of things to talk about
because this

25:28.427 --> 25:30.162 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
is a two-way relationship.

25:30.195 --> 25:35.401 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And for the Mexicans, they want
to help the
United States in the issues that
the United

25:35.434 --> 25:39.805 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
States is worried about, but
only if they
have a little bit of help, too.

25:39.838 --> 25:44.042 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, you know, Mexico, at this
point, has
largely been quiet.

25:44.076 --> 25:48.347 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They have taken a lot of bombast
from the
United States.

25:48.380 --> 25:53.752 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The president here, President
Pena Nieto,
has not been popular because he
has not really

25:53.786 --> 25:55.454 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
spat back at Trump.

25:55.487 --> 25:57.689 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But the Mexicans have a lot of
levers here.

25:57.723 --> 26:01.593 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They are the largest buyers, for
instance,
of corn in the United States.

26:01.627 --> 26:06.999 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They are the largest buyers of a
huge number
of other agricultural products
from the United

26:07.032 --> 26:08.801 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
States.

26:08.834 --> 26:13.639 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if things go south in this
relationship
-- it has gone south
tremendously over the

26:13.672 --> 26:14.640 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
last month.

26:14.673 --> 26:16.508 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Yes.

26:16.542 --> 26:19.445 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GARDINER HARRIS: If it gets
really worse,
the Mexicans can make things
hurt in the United

26:19.478 --> 26:23.615 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
States in places where the
United States really
doesn't want to have it go bad.

26:23.649 --> 26:27.453 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Yeganeh
Torbati, there has
been this narrative, fair or
unfair, that

26:27.486 --> 26:31.590 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the State Department has been
somewhat sidelined
in the major decision processes
that have

26:31.623 --> 26:35.327 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
already faced the Trump
administration and
perhaps, in certain times, they
have not even

26:35.360 --> 26:38.797 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
been consulted before executive
orders and
so forth are rolled out.

26:38.831 --> 26:42.067 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
YEGANEH TORBATI: I think that we
want to be
cautious.

26:42.100 --> 26:45.304 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Rex Tillerson has been on the
job for about
three weeks now.

26:45.337 --> 26:47.973 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Things are -- he's still sort of
getting his
bearings.

26:48.006 --> 26:52.978 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But it's true that we have a
number of data
points that suggest that there
isn't lot of

26:53.011 --> 26:54.546 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
consultation.

26:54.580 --> 26:57.616 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Of course, the State Department,
Rex Tillerson's
aides would push back on that.

26:57.649 --> 27:00.352 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They say he's in touch with
President Trump
several times a day.

27:00.385 --> 27:04.923 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But we know, from our reporting
and from others'
reporting, that he wasn't
consulted on any

27:04.957 --> 27:10.362 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
sort of change to the White
House language
regarding U.S. support for the
two-state solution,

27:10.395 --> 27:11.663 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
which happened last week.

27:11.697 --> 27:13.499 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That was a surprise to him.

27:13.532 --> 27:18.337 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we don't know if that is
deliberate, or
was it just sort of a result of
the chaos

27:18.370 --> 27:21.240 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that seems to be evident at the
White House
right now?

27:21.273 --> 27:24.009 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right,
Yeganeh Torbati
from Reuters, Gardiner Harris
from The New

27:24.042 --> 27:26.879 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
York Times, thank you both.

27:26.912 --> 27:35.354 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
YEGANEH TORBATI: Thank you.

27:35.387 --> 27:43.529 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: As we saw
earlier, President
Trump's top advisers presented a
picture of

27:43.562 --> 27:49.668 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
unity at the annual Conservative
Political
Action Conference, or CPAC, in
Maryland today.

27:49.701 --> 27:54.973 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Mr. Trump's chief strategist,
Steve Bannon,
and his chief of staff, Reince
Priebus, dismissed

27:55.007 --> 28:00.078 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the notion of any clashing
ideologies within
the president's inner circle.

28:00.112 --> 28:05.050 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
To discuss, we are joined by
former NPR CEO
Ken Stern.

28:05.083 --> 28:08.687 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He profiled Steve Bannon for
"Vanity Fair."

28:08.720 --> 28:13.158 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And Phil Rucker, he's White
House bureau chief
for The Washington Post.

28:13.191 --> 28:14.927 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And we welcome both of you to
the "NewsHour."

28:14.960 --> 28:17.095 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I'm going to start with you, Ken
Stern.

28:17.129 --> 28:20.999 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Fill out -- since you have
written about him,
fill out the picture of who
Steve Bannon is

28:21.033 --> 28:22.868 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and especially what does he
believe?

28:22.901 --> 28:27.172 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KEN STERN, Former CEO, NPR: So,
Steve -- just
little bit of background about
Steve Bannon.

28:27.205 --> 28:33.579 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He was a Goldman Sachs banker,
got wealthy
doing media deals.

28:33.612 --> 28:39.117 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Got into conservative media
doing documentaries
and met Andrew Breitbart, became
sort of friend

28:39.151 --> 28:40.252 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and counsel to him.

28:40.285 --> 28:43.755 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And then, when Andrew died, he
took over Breitbart.

28:43.789 --> 28:45.557 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And he transformed Breitbart.

28:45.591 --> 28:50.696 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When Andrew Breitbart ran it, it
was a site
that made a lot of noise,
attacked a lot of

28:50.729 --> 28:56.034 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
people in what he -- what Andrew
Breitbart
called the complex, the
Democratic Hollywood

28:56.068 --> 28:57.035 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
activists.

28:57.069 --> 28:58.837 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Right.

28:58.870 --> 29:04.710 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KEN STERN: And then -- but Steve
Bannon turned
it into a -- really a political
movement,

29:04.743 --> 29:09.514 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
a populist, nationalist
political movement
that I think Donald Trump
eventually rode

29:09.548 --> 29:11.216 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to power.

29:11.249 --> 29:13.352 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, Phil Rucker,
as somebody
who is covering the White House,
now, how

29:13.385 --> 29:18.123 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
much of that nationalist,
populist movement
has Steve Bannon brought to the
White House?

29:18.156 --> 29:20.792 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PHILIP RUCKER, The Washington
Post: All of
it.

29:20.826 --> 29:26.598 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You can point to many of the
acts that President
Trump has taken in his first
month in office,

29:26.632 --> 29:29.334 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and it's that agenda, it's that
ideology.

29:29.368 --> 29:31.970 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it's not so much that Bannon
is a puppeteer
here.

29:32.004 --> 29:36.308 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think it's more that Bannon
and Trump are
soul mates ideologically.

29:36.341 --> 29:40.946 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They both have the same views,
the same beliefs
about this sort of populism and
nationalism

29:40.979 --> 29:46.518 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and upending the kind of world
institutions
and structures that we have
become accustomed

29:46.551 --> 29:49.221 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to in the post-World War II era.

29:49.254 --> 29:54.526 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And you see it on domestic
policy, on trade,
on economic moves, and also
certainly in the

29:54.559 --> 29:55.894 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
foreign policy world.

29:55.927 --> 29:58.897 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Ken Stern, so
spell it out
for us.

29:58.930 --> 30:02.334 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Today, we heard Steve Bannon use
the term
economic nationalism.

30:02.367 --> 30:06.705 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He talked at one point about the
deconstruction
of the administrative state.

30:06.738 --> 30:08.473 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What is he saying he wants to
do?

30:08.507 --> 30:14.613 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KEN STERN: I think he wants to
change the
neo-liberal world order away
from free trade,

30:14.646 --> 30:17.149 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
away from open borders.

30:17.182 --> 30:19.051 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's America first.

30:19.084 --> 30:25.257 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It is a philosophy built on the
notion that
virtue lies with the people, and
the establishment

30:25.290 --> 30:28.427 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
has stabbed the people in the
back.

30:28.460 --> 30:30.362 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And he wants to change that
world.

30:30.395 --> 30:32.597 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You're saying,
yes, Phil Rucker.

30:32.631 --> 30:34.700 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PHILIP RUCKER: That's exactly
right.

30:34.733 --> 30:36.768 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And it's interesting the
language that Bannon
used.

30:36.802 --> 30:40.706 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
These are not terms that we
often hear in
the political mainstream.

30:40.739 --> 30:46.078 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, in fact, some of the words
like globalist,
corporatist are terms you hear
on the political

30:46.111 --> 30:48.814 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
left, like the Bernie Sanders
campaign.

30:48.847 --> 30:52.217 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But this is a really different
kind of movement
here.

30:52.250 --> 30:55.087 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It's not traditional
Republicanism.

30:55.120 --> 31:00.392 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's nationalism, it's populism,
it's changing
the structures and the way
things work politically

31:00.425 --> 31:03.628 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and economically in the world
and here at
home.

31:03.662 --> 31:07.966 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Phil Rucker,
staying with you,
they did, as we were reporting
earlier, try

31:07.999 --> 31:09.801 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to paint a portrait of unity
today.

31:09.835 --> 31:11.603 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
PHILIP RUCKER: That's right.

31:11.636 --> 31:14.039 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You would think
that Reince
Priebus and Steve Bannon were
the dearest

31:14.072 --> 31:16.074 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
friends from way back.

31:16.108 --> 31:19.211 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What has it really been like
inside the White
House with them?

31:19.244 --> 31:21.747 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PHILIP RUCKER: Well, it's
changed a little
bit.

31:21.780 --> 31:25.717 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think early on in the White
House, there
were these competing power
structures that

31:25.751 --> 31:31.523 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
President Trump set up on
purpose, Bannon
as chief strategist, Reince
Priebus as chief

31:31.556 --> 31:33.358 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of staff.

31:33.391 --> 31:37.496 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we were getting reports of
some tension,
not only between them, but among
their allies

31:37.529 --> 31:39.197 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
within the administration.

31:39.231 --> 31:41.032 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But that seems to have cooled
off a bit.

31:41.066 --> 31:44.736 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There was a point a couple of
weeks in where
President Trump told all of his
aides in the

31:44.770 --> 31:49.307 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Oval Office, look, Reince
Priebus is in charge,
he is the chief of staff, the
process runs

31:49.341 --> 31:50.375 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
through him.

31:50.408 --> 31:52.277 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I think Bannon has adapted
to that.

31:52.310 --> 31:57.349 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And Bannon is more the ideas
guy, the strategist,
the person kind of coming up
with the grand

31:57.382 --> 32:02.220 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
plan, whereas Reince Priebus is
the one implementing
it and orchestrating the process
and dealing

32:02.254 --> 32:05.857 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
with kind of the hour-to-hour,
day-by-day
activities of the White House.

32:05.891 --> 32:10.796 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Ken Stern, so
based on what
you know about Steve Bannon, how
do you see

32:10.829 --> 32:13.165 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
him operating in this White
House?

32:13.198 --> 32:18.503 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Because, as we heard Phil Rucker
say, he and
the president see eye to eye on
a lot.

32:18.537 --> 32:20.172 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
So, how does he make his
influence felt?

32:20.205 --> 32:22.541 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KEN STERN: Well, I tend to think
-- so, I
agree with Phil.

32:22.574 --> 32:29.181 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I tend to think of Bannon as the
chief ideologist
of the White House, the ideas
guy, the guy

32:29.214 --> 32:30.982 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
who is a political philosopher.

32:31.016 --> 32:34.452 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You even heard it today, the way
they talked.

32:34.486 --> 32:37.656 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Bannon talked about
deconstructing the
administrative
state.

32:37.689 --> 32:41.593 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Priebus talked about two-for-one
exchanges
of regulations.

32:41.626 --> 32:44.663 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Bannon is the big idea guy.

32:44.696 --> 32:46.464 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Priebus is the tactician.

32:46.498 --> 32:49.467 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But does that
mean that Reince
Priebus is going to be prepared
to go along

32:49.501 --> 32:53.238 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
with all this agenda that Steve
Bannon espouses?

32:53.271 --> 32:56.875 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
KEN STERN: I think this is very
strange bedfellows.

32:56.908 --> 32:58.743 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You know what they say about
politics.

32:58.777 --> 33:03.648 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But if you went back to
Breitbart, and during
the early part of the election,
before Bannon

33:03.682 --> 33:08.253 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
joined the campaign, public
enemy number one
for Breitbart is the Republican
establishment.

33:08.286 --> 33:14.259 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They ran Paul -- they supported
Paul Nehlen
against Speaker Ryan.

33:14.292 --> 33:18.697 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They don't like people -- the
things that
Reince Priebus stands for.

33:18.730 --> 33:20.799 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, it's a very odd collection.

33:20.832 --> 33:23.535 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And they may -- they seem
genuinely to get
along.

33:23.568 --> 33:25.470 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They may be just good actors.

33:25.503 --> 33:28.773 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But there has got to be
long-term tension
between the establishment and
the anti-establishment.

33:28.807 --> 33:32.644 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What is your
sense of that,
Phil Rucker?

33:32.677 --> 33:38.717 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You are saying that they seem to
be working
together better in the last few
weeks, but

33:38.750 --> 33:44.456 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
what is the -- is there a fear,
is there a
concern about Bannon having too
much influence

33:44.489 --> 33:46.124 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
over the president?

33:46.157 --> 33:48.426 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
How does the rest of the White
House staff
read him?

33:48.460 --> 33:52.564 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PHILIP RUCKER: You know, there
is some concern
about that, but people have to
remember, it's

33:52.597 --> 33:53.565 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
not just Bannon.

33:53.598 --> 33:56.601 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I mean, Bannon is espousing
Trump's views.

33:56.635 --> 34:00.338 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So if you're going to war with
Bannon, you're
going to war with the president,
too.

34:00.372 --> 34:04.042 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think the more traditional
Republicans
in the White House, even if they
have been

34:04.075 --> 34:08.880 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
schooled to think differently
about these
issues ideologically, and even
if they personally

34:08.914 --> 34:12.217 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
might feel something different,
this is Trump's
belief.

34:12.250 --> 34:13.218 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It's his agenda.

34:13.251 --> 34:14.552 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's his world view.

34:14.586 --> 34:17.923 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's the things that he is
trying to implement
as president.

34:17.956 --> 34:21.159 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And Bannon is guiding him and
leading him
in that direction.

34:21.192 --> 34:25.230 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But the other staffers have to
kind of go
along, or get lost, if you will.

34:25.263 --> 34:28.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And that sounds
like the makings
of a tense situation, Ken Stern.

34:28.366 --> 34:29.534 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
KEN STERN: It does.

34:29.567 --> 34:31.269 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It really does.

34:31.303 --> 34:35.774 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, it's
certainly something
that has all our attention right
now.

34:35.807 --> 34:39.411 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Ken Stern, Phil Rucker, we thank
you both.

34:39.444 --> 34:43.882 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
PHILIP RUCKER: Thank you.

34:43.915 --> 34:49.454 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
KEN STERN: Thank you, Judy.

34:49.487 --> 34:52.424 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
