a high school
graduate fell by 19 percent.

36:55.847 --> 37:02.420 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well away from the Ivory Tower,
on the ground
in Maysville, Wayne Pendleton
has lived the

37:02.454 --> 37:04.189 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
change.

37:04.222 --> 37:05.223 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WAYNE PENDLETON, Kentucky:
Maysville, when
we moved here, was a pretty well
flourishing

37:05.256 --> 37:06.991 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
little town right here.

37:07.025 --> 37:09.427 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But we have lived here, what, 17
years?

37:09.461 --> 37:12.297 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And you can just name the stuff
that's left
here.

37:12.330 --> 37:16.734 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You can't take a job away from a
guy 55 years
old and expect him to start all
over again.

37:16.768 --> 37:20.805 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SHERMAN SAUNDERS, Kentucky: Even
at my age,
it's depressing if you're not
trying to do

37:20.839 --> 37:22.373 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
something.

37:22.407 --> 37:25.777 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Despite four heart
attacks, Sherman
Saunders still wants to work.

37:25.810 --> 37:28.680 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SHERMAN SAUNDERS: That's not
someone else's
responsibility to take care of
the family.

37:28.713 --> 37:30.515 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's supposed to be yours.

37:30.548 --> 37:34.219 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You have to go to work to do
that yourself.

37:34.252 --> 37:36.054 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARCY CONNER, Nurse: Most of the
men aren't
working.

37:36.087 --> 37:39.190 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Marcy Conner, a
nurse specializing
in substance abuse, has a
close-up view of

37:39.224 --> 37:40.325 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the downward spiral.

37:40.358 --> 37:42.694 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARCY CONNER: All of a sudden,
you lose your
job.

37:42.727 --> 37:45.663 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, here is a male with no
identity.

37:45.697 --> 37:46.664 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
He's not working.

37:46.698 --> 37:48.099 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He's supposed to be a provider
for his family.

37:48.133 --> 37:50.335 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
He can't even do that.

37:50.368 --> 37:57.375 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So that low self-worth, along
with that hopelessness
feeling, we start seeing
tremendous depression.

37:57.408 --> 38:00.111 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
So, how do you relieve
depression?

38:00.145 --> 38:03.882 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You can relieve it with drug
use, alcohol
use, or suicide.

38:03.915 --> 38:06.684 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Conner's own
husband died of
alcohol poisoning.

38:06.718 --> 38:11.055 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARCY CONNER: Poured alcohol
down his feeding
tube until he died.

38:11.089 --> 38:14.659 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: The husband of best
friend Becky
Manning also killed himself.

38:14.692 --> 38:17.262 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BECKY MANNING, Widow: He blew
his head off.

38:17.295 --> 38:21.299 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Joseph Manning had
been a truck
driver for 30 years.

38:21.332 --> 38:27.805 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BECKY MANNING: And then he
retired at 55,
which then gave him nothing to
do.

38:27.839 --> 38:30.842 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Then he started getting
depressed.

38:30.875 --> 38:38.750 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And then we would go to
different doctors,
and then they would just try
different drugs.

38:38.783 --> 38:42.987 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And those never worked, because
they caused
side effects, which made him
feel worse about

38:43.021 --> 38:43.988 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
himself.

38:44.022 --> 38:45.056 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Right, weight gain?

38:45.089 --> 38:47.091 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BECKY MANNING: Yes, he gained
weight.

38:47.125 --> 38:48.092 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: Libido?

38:48.126 --> 38:51.062 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BECKY MANNING: Absolutely, where
I'm worthless.

38:51.095 --> 38:53.631 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I can't be here for my wife, you
know?

38:53.665 --> 38:59.704 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: So when you hear
about the end
of work, the jobs, like truck
driving jobs...

38:59.737 --> 39:00.705 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
BECKY MANNING: Right.

39:00.738 --> 39:01.706 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: ... which will be
replaced by...

39:01.739 --> 39:02.707 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
BECKY MANNING: Absolutely.

39:02.740 --> 39:04.042 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: ... self driving
cars, you think?

39:04.075 --> 39:06.277 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BECKY MANNING: What are these
men going to
do?

39:06.311 --> 39:08.179 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Yes.

39:08.213 --> 39:12.383 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCY CONNER: In this next
generation, I think
you're going to see the death
rate continue

39:12.417 --> 39:14.319 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to climb.

39:14.352 --> 39:19.257 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Local doctor Craig
Denham buys
into the economic hypothesis.

39:19.290 --> 39:20.758 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

39:20.792 --> 39:23.061 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM CRAIG DENHAM, Family
Physician: Economics
is a major component.

39:23.094 --> 39:24.829 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Job availability is a major
component.

39:24.862 --> 39:27.665 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: So, case closed.

39:27.699 --> 39:33.104 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Economics explains the epidemic
of suicide
and overdose deaths ravaging
America's white

39:33.137 --> 39:34.105 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
working-class.

39:34.138 --> 39:36.708 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Not so fast, say Case and
Deaton.

39:36.741 --> 39:43.147 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANNE CASE: Because Europeans
have suffered
too in this -- the jobs leaving
the country,

39:43.181 --> 39:45.216 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
but we don't see them killing
themselves.

39:45.250 --> 39:47.151 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ANGUS DEATON: Yes, you know,
Spain suffered.

39:47.185 --> 39:51.990 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The unemployment rate went from
5 percent
to like 25 percent.

39:52.023 --> 39:53.258 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And the health improved.

39:53.291 --> 39:55.426 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: And what about
working-class
black Americans?

39:55.460 --> 40:00.465 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANNE CASE: African-Americans'
rates of death
from suicide, drug overdose and
alcohol have

40:00.498 --> 40:01.499 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
been flat.

40:01.532 --> 40:03.334 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
They have not risen.

40:03.368 --> 40:06.371 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DARRICK HAMILTON, Economist:
It's not as if
stress is something new to the
black American

40:06.404 --> 40:07.572 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
population.

40:07.605 --> 40:08.873 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have been dealing with stress
for quite
a long time.

40:08.906 --> 40:10.642 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Economist Darrick
Hamilton.

40:10.675 --> 40:13.778 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DARRICK HAMILTON: The impact of
stress is
not new, so that's why you're
probably not

40:13.811 --> 40:17.015 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
seeing an uptick the way it is
for whites.

40:17.048 --> 40:19.684 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We're used to struggle,
unfortunately.

40:19.717 --> 40:25.290 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANGUS DEATON: And also there's
this argument
on the other side that whites
have been ahead

40:25.323 --> 40:30.628 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for so long that, when they see
their world
coming apart, even though
they're still doing

40:30.662 --> 40:34.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
much better than blacks, then
they see equalization
as oppression.

40:34.899 --> 40:40.938 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBERT FRANK, Economist: The
group that they
studied is one that has, by
almost every concrete

40:40.972 --> 40:43.741 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
measure, been falling behind in
recent decades.

40:43.775 --> 40:48.846 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Economist Bob Frank
has devoted
much of his career to the study
of inequality.

40:48.880 --> 40:52.116 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ROBERT FRANK: Life is graded on
the curve.

40:52.150 --> 40:54.319 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's not how well you do in
absolute terms.

40:54.352 --> 40:57.288 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's how well you do relative to
your competitors.

40:57.322 --> 40:59.324 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Or relative to your
own past.

40:59.357 --> 41:05.196 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBERT FRANK: And if you're in a
chronic loser
position, I think that's a
position that just

41:05.229 --> 41:07.098 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
wears people down eventually.

41:07.131 --> 41:13.471 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Psychologically and
physiologically,
as low status is linked to
decreased serotonin

41:13.504 --> 41:19.677 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in the brain, which can cause
dysphoria, a
state of intense unease and
distress.

41:19.711 --> 41:25.450 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBERT FRANK: If you're exposed
to having
low status in a chronic way and
experiencing

41:25.483 --> 41:31.456 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
protracted feelings of
dysphoria, it's not
surprising that many people
would turn to

41:31.489 --> 41:35.393 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
drink and drugs as a way to
alleviate such
feelings.

41:35.426 --> 41:37.829 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: In fact, according
to a recent
study by

41:37.862 --> 41:42.967 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
economist Alan Krueger,
middle-aged men who
have dropped out of the labor
force report

41:43.000 --> 41:49.707 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
notably low levels of emotional
well-being,
and more than half take pain
medication every

41:49.741 --> 41:51.476 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
day.

41:51.509 --> 41:55.246 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANGUS DEATON: And so, if you
suffer enough,
and your kids are not doing very
well, and

41:55.279 --> 42:02.520 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the world's going to hell in a
handbasket,
then suicide, either directly or
through painkillers

42:02.553 --> 42:07.892 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
or alcohol, might seem like a
not completely
crazy thing to do.

42:07.925 --> 42:12.663 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: There is, we should
acknowledge,
another take on the rise in
so-called deaths

42:12.697 --> 42:14.532 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of despair.

42:14.565 --> 42:18.169 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANTHONY FLANNERY, Kentucky: I
don't buy into
the everything fell apart, so
now I just -- I

42:18.202 --> 42:19.170 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
can't do nothing.

42:19.203 --> 42:21.072 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I still believe in the American
dream.

42:21.105 --> 42:24.776 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Anthony Flannery,
who works long
hours in health care, and on
funding his dream

42:24.809 --> 42:28.780 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of making music full-time,
doesn't dispute
the data.

42:28.813 --> 42:32.784 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He just doesn't think they
provide an excuse
or even much of an explanation.

42:32.817 --> 42:37.021 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANTHONY FLANNERY: So people that
lay around
and give up, I don't relate to
it.

42:37.054 --> 42:41.492 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's like, OK, I can understand
getting knocked
down, and now you, oh, I don't
know what to

42:41.526 --> 42:42.460 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
do.

42:42.493 --> 42:43.461 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I'm overwhelmed.

42:43.494 --> 42:44.462 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I get that.

42:44.495 --> 42:46.264 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I have been there countless
times.

42:46.297 --> 42:50.101 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But you have to get focused,
pick yourself
up, find a direction, and make
it happen in

42:50.134 --> 42:51.869 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
your life and for your family.

42:51.903 --> 42:57.175 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But if the problem
is a decline
in moral fiber, what would
explain that?

42:57.208 --> 43:02.613 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Too easy access to remedies that
seem to cure
all problems, until they become
the problem

43:02.647 --> 43:10.087 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
themselves, or, longer term, the
deteriorating
economics of white working-age
America, relative

43:10.121 --> 43:13.024 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to any and all expectations?

43:13.057 --> 43:23.334 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
For the "PBS NewsHour,"
economics correspondent
Paul Solman, reporting from
Kentucky.

43:23.367 --> 43:35.680 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Next month, the
Syrian civil
war will enter its sixth year.

43:35.713 --> 43:41.986 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The United Nations estimates
that more than
400,000 Syrians have been
killed, and more

43:42.019 --> 43:46.724 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
than 10 million people have
either fled the
country or been displaced within
it since

43:46.757 --> 43:48.593 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the war began.

43:48.626 --> 43:54.131 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A documentary that's up for an
Oscar on Sunday
attempts to put a human face on
that conflict.

43:54.165 --> 43:58.736 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown has the story for
our series
Beyond the Red Carpet.

43:58.769 --> 44:06.010 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: They are images
at once shocking
and strangely familiar, the
daily destruction

44:06.043 --> 44:10.314 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of Syria's civil war.

44:10.348 --> 44:15.019 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But the Oscar-nominated
documentary short
"The White Helmets" aims to get
beyond the

44:15.052 --> 44:18.589 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
numbness of this conflict now
dragging into
its sixth year.

44:18.623 --> 44:21.192 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ORLANDO VON EINSIEDEL, Director,
"The White
Helmets": The Syria conflict has
been going

44:21.225 --> 44:23.928 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
on for so long, it's so
upsetting, and people
feel so powerless.

44:23.961 --> 44:27.431 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the story of the White
Helmets is a story
of hope.

44:27.465 --> 44:32.904 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Director Orlando
Von Einsiedel
and producer Joanna Natasegara
are best known

44:32.937 --> 44:39.343 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
for "Virunga," their
Oscar-nominated 2014
documentary about a team of
Congolese National

44:39.377 --> 44:42.947 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Park guards who protect gorillas
from poachers.

44:42.980 --> 44:48.152 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In "The White Helmets," they
profile a volunteer
group of first-responders
working to rescue

44:48.185 --> 44:55.126 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
victims of the ongoing assault
on cities like
Aleppo, a group that's been
featured on this

44:55.159 --> 44:56.994 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
news program and others.

44:57.028 --> 45:02.900 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, since 2013, the White
Helmets, whose official
name is the Syrian Civil
Defense, has, by

45:02.934 --> 45:09.140 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
some estimates, saved 70,000
people.

45:09.173 --> 45:18.149 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ORLANDO VON EINSIEDEL: What we
found most
extraordinary was who the rescue
workers were,

45:18.182 --> 45:24.889 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this group of everyday Syrian
civilians who
had decided not to pick up a
gun, had decided

45:24.922 --> 45:30.428 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
not to leave Syria, and instead
had decided
to stay and every day risk their
lives to

45:30.461 --> 45:32.597 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
save their fellow citizens.

45:32.630 --> 45:36.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And they're builders, tailors,
bakers, just
normal people.

45:36.534 --> 45:37.969 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They're truly real-life heroes.

45:38.002 --> 45:39.770 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: What was it like
to meet them?

45:39.804 --> 45:42.039 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOANNA NATASEGARA, Producer,
"The White Helmets":
It was really nerve-racking at
first.

45:42.073 --> 45:47.078 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We didn't know if they would
live up to this
incredible story we that we
thought we had

45:47.111 --> 45:48.913 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
found.

45:48.946 --> 45:52.149 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, actually, what we found was
people that
were even more heroic and
inspiring than we

45:52.183 --> 45:53.918 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
had thought.

45:53.951 --> 45:58.389 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: There is this
moment in which
a baby is rescued from the
rubble, which is

45:58.422 --> 45:59.890 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
just incredible.

45:59.924 --> 46:10.034 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's almost -- you couldn't
believe you're
watching what you're seeing.

46:10.034 --> 46:18.476 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's almost -- you couldn't
believe you're
watching what you're seeing.

46:18.509 --> 46:29.720 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ORLANDO VON EINSIEDEL: Yes.

46:29.754 --> 46:37.161 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's -- the tragedy is, scenes
like that are
playing out every day inside
Syria.

46:37.194 --> 46:43.601 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But this particular rescue, the
very fact
that it's been documented, it
acts as a moment

46:43.634 --> 46:47.972 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of hope and something to rally
around that,
really, there is still hope in
Syria and there

46:48.005 --> 46:50.374 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
are very brave people doing
incredible work.

46:50.408 --> 46:54.912 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: For safety
reasons, interviews
and some of the filming were
done in Turkey,

46:54.945 --> 46:57.948 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
near the border and away from
the immediate
danger.

46:57.982 --> 47:00.885 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But the filmmakers found a way
to get a close-up
view.

47:00.918 --> 47:07.024 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOANNA NATASEGARA: Usually, in
our work, we
would be on site in a location
even in a war

47:07.058 --> 47:08.826 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
zone filming ourselves.

47:08.859 --> 47:12.797 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But in this situation, the White
Helmets themselves
said: Please don't, please don't
do that,

47:12.830 --> 47:16.934 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
because, actually, you put our
teams at greater
risk as well.

47:16.967 --> 47:19.070 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, luckily, we didn't need to.

47:19.103 --> 47:24.775 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We found -- we were very lucky
to find a young
White Helmet called Khaled
Khateeb whose work

47:24.809 --> 47:27.578 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in photography had been used by
The New York
Times.

47:27.611 --> 47:31.849 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so we brought him out to the
Turkish-Syrian
border, and we paired him with
our own cinematographer.

47:31.882 --> 47:36.921 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they worked together for
five weeks to
really -- you know, to learn a
common language.

47:36.954 --> 47:40.524 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Were there
surprises for you
in this process?

47:40.558 --> 47:43.928 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I assume you knew something
about it going
in, but...

47:43.961 --> 47:48.799 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ORLANDO VON EINSIEDEL: I think
we knew going
into this project just how --
the physical

47:48.833 --> 47:52.737 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
stress and the physical violence
that the
White Helmets experience on a
daily basis.

47:52.770 --> 47:57.141 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But we were really shocked by
the emotional
toll this work takes on them.

47:57.174 --> 48:01.846 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And even inside Turkey, which is
relatively
safe, the guys at the end of the
training

48:01.879 --> 48:06.450 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
every day, when they got their
phones and
