50:02.499 --> 50:15.246 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Now to our
Brief But Spectacular
series, where we ask people to
describe their

50:15.279 --> 50:17.248 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
passions.

50:17.281 --> 50:21.752 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Kathleen Collins was one of the
first African-American
women to direct a feature film,
"Losing Ground."

50:21.785 --> 50:26.023 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Having passed away from cancer
in 1988, she
is remembered tonight by her
daughter, Nina

50:26.056 --> 50:27.825 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Collins.

50:27.858 --> 50:31.362 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Nearly 30 years after her death,
Collins has
restored her mother's work,
including a book

50:31.395 --> 50:35.332 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of her short stories, entitled
"Whatever Happened
To Interracial Love?"

50:35.366 --> 50:38.168 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NINA COLLINS, Daughter of
Kathleen Collins:
My mother was one of the first
black women,

50:38.202 --> 50:41.405 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think the second black woman
to make a feature
film in America.

50:41.438 --> 50:43.874 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
She wrote, produced, and
directed "Losing
Ground."

50:43.908 --> 50:45.876 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
She made the film in 1982.

50:45.910 --> 50:50.047 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This was before "The Cosby
Show," which, for
me, was the big time we really
saw black middle-class

50:50.080 --> 50:51.849 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Americans in popular culture.

50:51.882 --> 50:53.484 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Really, it had just not been
seen.

50:53.517 --> 51:02.159 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think that was why the films
weren't released
in their time.

51:02.192 --> 51:08.632 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I turned 47 this year, and my
mother died
when she was 46.

51:08.666 --> 51:11.235 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And last year was a difficult,
complicated
year for me.

51:11.268 --> 51:12.236 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Her work was being released.

51:12.269 --> 51:15.639 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I was the same age she was when
she died.

51:15.673 --> 51:20.778 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I was really lucky to have a
mother who made
me feel like I could definitely
do anything.

51:20.811 --> 51:24.081 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She was enormously capable, but
it was also
hard.

51:24.114 --> 51:25.549 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I think she was pretty
depressed.

51:25.582 --> 51:26.784 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
She was always writing.

51:26.817 --> 51:29.887 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She was always in her room
typing and kind
of distracted.

51:29.920 --> 51:34.091 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She had first gotten cancer when
I was 11,
and then had a recurrence when I
was 15, and

51:34.124 --> 51:36.360 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
then a third recurrence when I
was 18.

51:36.393 --> 51:38.162 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And she kept all of that a
secret from me.

51:38.195 --> 51:40.564 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Then I went off to study abroad
for a year.

51:40.597 --> 51:43.534 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I came home from Europe, and she
was very,
very sick.

51:43.567 --> 51:45.602 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And she died two weeks later.

51:45.636 --> 51:50.074 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the only thing that she was
explicit about
was that she wanted me to take
care of my

51:50.107 --> 51:51.842 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
brother.

51:51.875 --> 51:55.312 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was incredibly stressful, and
we had no
money, and I felt abandoned and
didn't know

51:55.346 --> 51:57.047 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
what to do.

51:57.081 --> 51:59.450 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I collected all of her
writing that I
could find and her photographs
and copies

51:59.483 --> 52:02.286 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of everything, and put it in
this big trunk
that I found in our house.

52:02.319 --> 52:04.588 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I really couldn't go through it.

52:04.621 --> 52:06.457 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It was just too painful.

52:06.490 --> 52:11.128 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then, in my 30s, so, you
know, almost
20 years later, I was going
through a difficult

52:11.161 --> 52:18.135 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
time in my own life and kind of
realized that
I hadn't looked at my history
enough.

52:18.168 --> 52:22.039 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I started looking through this
trunk and reading
her journals and her letters.

52:22.072 --> 52:27.711 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There were screenplays and plays
and short
stories that I had never read
and an unfinished

52:27.745 --> 52:28.679 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
novel.

52:28.712 --> 52:30.547 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It was a huge treasure trove of
material.

52:30.581 --> 52:34.585 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I had "Losing Ground" restored
really so that
it wouldn't be lost.

52:34.618 --> 52:37.621 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
When the Lincoln Center
announced that they
wanted it for this festival, we
didn't expect

52:37.654 --> 52:39.156 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
what happened to happen.

52:39.189 --> 52:40.791 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, suddenly, we started getting
all these
reviews.

52:40.824 --> 52:45.229 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I woke up to a "New Yorker"
review on my phone,
and I just couldn't stop crying.

52:45.262 --> 52:48.098 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, it's very bittersweet.

52:48.132 --> 52:50.167 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
She's been dead now almost 30
years.

52:50.200 --> 52:54.905 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I can't imagine what she
would feel if
she knew all these things had
happened.

52:54.938 --> 52:57.141 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I feel like I'm championing my
mother.

52:57.174 --> 52:58.909 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I'm bringing her work to light.

52:58.942 --> 53:02.212 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I'm also working through my
own relationship
with her.

53:02.246 --> 53:08.385 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think, as I get older, I'm
able to understand
better what she was going
through and to forgive

53:08.419 --> 53:12.022 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
her for some of the things that
I missed.

53:12.056 --> 53:16.360 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
My name is Nina Collins, and
this is my Brief
But Spectacular take on my
mother.

